177	/**
178		A "Player" as an entity that contains the persistent info of the Player, as well as containing 
179		transient mission data.
180	
181		Some of the Player's attributes persist between missions, whereas others are "transient" and only 
182		have meaning in a mission, wherein they change a lot (current tech tree state, current buildings 
183		built, units trained, money, etc). (For clarity of nomenclature, we'll refer to all "persistent"
184		vs "non-persistent" attributes, since "transient" has an unclear duration.)
185	
186		A "Player" consists of an entity controlling a single set of units in a mission. 
187		A Player may be human or computer controlled. 
188	
189		All Players have a (transient) "Player Index" associated which allows us to do some shorthand for
190		representing Players in some cases (mainly in bitfields). This is always a 0-based
191		number (-1 is used as an illegal index). Note that a logical conclusion of this
192		is that it makes it desirable to limit the maximum number of simultaneous Players
193		to 32, but that seems quite reasonable.
194	
195		All persistent data associated with the Player will be saved to local storage and/or 
196		synchronized with one of our servers for online play. 
197	
198		Note, simple accessor methods are omitted for brevity... for now, you may infer
199		them from the data structures.
200	
201		Note also that the class (and the relevant subclasses) are almost certainly incomplete;
202		a short perusal of the RA2 equivalent class(es) have waaay more tweaky data fields,
203		some of which will probably be necessary (in some form, at some point), some of
204		which won't ever be necessary. Rather than trying to guess at all of them here,
205		we're limiting the initial setup to be the almost-certainly-necessary, filling in
206		the extra things as needed. (Note that most of these will be non-persistent!)
207	*/
